 apply to this tradition. The approach adopted is cross-disciplinary in orientation to reflect the centrality of taclil in the Arabic intellectual tradition, and reference is therefore made to the employment of this concept in jurisprudence and, to a lesser extent, theology. This is the first major study in any European language or in Arabic to be published on the topic. It will be of interest to Arabic grammarians, students of Arabic and general linguistics and to specialists in Islamic jurisprudence and philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArabic languagexGrammarxHistory. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Grammar & Punctuation.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311078047540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447292040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474472920423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474472920/original  a978-3-11-078047-5  Edinburgh University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK